if you already have git with bash installed on your windows machine i think the easiest way to generate and use ssh key would be:
• generate a key locally
 `ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 -c "<email-address>`
-t type of encryption -b 4096 strength of encryption
• list the generated key
`ls | grep <keyname>`
• copy your public key
`cat <keyname.pub>`

to ssh into any remote machine you can use:
•  start the ssh-agent in the background 
`$ eval "$(ssh-add -s)" >`
output : agent pid 59566
• add your ssh private key to the ssh-agent
 `$ ssh-add <pathtoyourprivatekeyfile>/<yourprivatekeyname>`
